 This brings the positivity rate to 9.7 percent, down from Saturday’s 13 percent. Of the cases, 220 are Kenyans while 41 are foreigners;  134 are males and 127. The youngest case is that of a one-year-old child, and the oldest patient is 94 years old. Total confirmed positive cases are now 332,227 out of 3,744,829 tests conducted so far. The infections were distributed across various counties as follows: Nairobi 155, Kiambu 31, Laikipia 24, Garissa 7, Machakos 6, Tana River 6, Kajiado 5, Mombasa 5, Busia 4, Nakuru 4, Kisumu 3, Siaya 3, Meru 3, Bungoma 2, Embu, Kakamega and Kilifi 1 case each. According to Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe, 426 patients have recovered from the disease which has claimed one life in the past 24 hours. Cumulative fatalities currently stand at  5,652. "There are 118 patients currently admitted in our health facilities, while 3,790 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care 4 program," said Kagwe.